 of this revolutionary approach, Self-Direction describes the development of this movement through the authors' personal accounts. Also included are stories from actual participants in the movement who benefitted from this approach and from policymakers who saw how self-direction could help address states' problems. The book's conclusion discusses recommendations that can improve the way self-direction is delivered and how to spread its message so that all people with disabilities can have this choice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aAutonomy (Psychology). 0aHuman services. 4aCultural Studies : Disabilities. 4aCultural Studies : Gerontology/Aging Studies. 4aPublic Policy : Public Policy. 4aSociology : Social Problems. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Social Services & Welfare.2bisacsh1 aFenton, Marc H., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aMahoney, Kevin J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2021z978311149169140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143848344340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438483443423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438483443/original  a978-3-11-149169-1  SUNY Press eBook Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles